You know what I prefer?
I prefer dollars.

16:36.695 --> 16:38.363
If you want to go on
down to 40 broad,

16:38.365 --> 16:41.265
right next door to
the stock exchange there,

16:41.267 --> 16:43.668
to the New York bitcoin center,

16:43.670 --> 16:46.137
you can buy and sell
all the time.

16:55.514 --> 16:58.049
- You have a table
in the middle.
- Yeah.

16:58.051 --> 17:00.585
Just one small table, round.

17:00.587 --> 17:05.522
And I have flowers,
like a flower arrangement.

17:05.525 --> 17:07.791
- A very nice
flower arrangement.
- Bitcoin flowers?

17:07.794 --> 17:10.127
Bitcoin flowers.
Bitcoin flowers would be

17:10.130 --> 17:13.097
white Lily, purple and orange.

17:13.098 --> 17:14.766
Just right here, three colors.

17:17.336 --> 17:21.204
We're putting together
the first bitcoin center

17:21.207 --> 17:22.640
here in New York City,

17:22.642 --> 17:25.309
right next door to
the New York stock exchange

17:25.310 --> 17:28.079
bitcoin is a new space,

17:28.080 --> 17:32.350
and many of the rules
and regulations haven't
been imposed yet.

17:32.352 --> 17:35.586
But we will open one day soon,

17:35.588 --> 17:39.490
after the lawyers do their job,

17:39.492 --> 17:43.461
a live digital currency
exchange.

17:43.463 --> 17:46.097
What's happening here
is a fusion between

17:46.099 --> 17:49.700
wall street and bitcoin,
hopefully.

17:51.170 --> 17:53.738
Satoshi seemed to acknowledge

17:53.740 --> 17:57.575
that it would be hard
for bitcoin to develop
in any way

17:57.577 --> 18:02.246
in which it wasn't interacting
with the regular economy

18:02.248 --> 18:04.549
of dollars and Euros.

18:04.551 --> 18:06.484
The problem with exchanges is

18:06.486 --> 18:09.687
that they took you back
to this old world

18:09.689 --> 18:12.390
that bitcoin was really
trying to get away from.

18:12.392 --> 18:15.827
As soon as you move
back to an exchange,

18:15.829 --> 18:18.429
you're moving back to a world

18:18.431 --> 18:23.401
in which some third party
has all this personal data
on you,

18:23.403 --> 18:24.702
has all of your money,

18:24.704 --> 18:26.838
has all of the security
vulnerabilities,

18:26.840 --> 18:29.240
and really has none
of those strengths

18:29.242 --> 18:34.345
that bitcoin
was designed to provide.

18:34.347 --> 18:36.380
Jed mccaleb
created mt. Gox,

18:36.382 --> 18:38.282
essentially on a lark one night

18:38.284 --> 18:42.420
because he couldn't
buy bitcoins as quickly
as he wanted to.

18:42.422 --> 18:44.822
And interestingly,
he did it by starting

18:44.824 --> 18:47.458
with a url
that he'd previously used

18:47.460 --> 18:50.361
to run magic card trading sites.

18:50.363 --> 18:53.231
So you get an idea
about where somebody's ideas
are coming from

18:53.233 --> 18:56.334
and how really kind of
rudimentary some of them were.

18:56.336 --> 18:59.504
Jed essentially threw
this site together,

18:59.506 --> 19:03.674
and put it online without
too much thought.

19:14.820 --> 19:18.689
Jed essentially sold it
to the first person he found.

19:18.691 --> 19:20.892
Who was mark karpeles,
a French guy

19:20.894 --> 19:22.560
who was living in Tokyo.

19:22.562 --> 19:24.929
He really knew
very little about mark

19:24.931 --> 19:27.231
when he decided
to sell it to him.

19:27.233 --> 19:29.567
And once he took it over,

19:29.569 --> 19:32.236
it began growing
much more quickly

19:32.238 --> 19:35.806
than mark was expecting
or was prepared for.

19:46.652 --> 19:48.452
There are 21 million bitcoins

19:48.454 --> 19:50.321
programmed into the system
that are going to be released.

19:50.323 --> 19:52.256
It's a set number,
but within that,

19:52.258 --> 19:54.592
every single bitcoin
can be divided up

19:54.594 --> 19:56.794
into a hundred million
different pieces

19:56.796 --> 19:59.864
so there's room for it
to expand as the use expands,

19:59.866 --> 20:03.334
especially in
the emerging markets,
in the developing world.

20:03.336 --> 20:05.536
That is really
the most interesting place

20:05.538 --> 20:07.872
to see where this thing goes.

20:07.874 --> 20:10.875
So in my pocket I have
a hundred trillion
Zimbabwe dollars

20:10.877 --> 20:12.510
from the reserve bank
of Zimbabwe,

20:12.512 --> 20:14.478
just as a reminder
of what happens

20:14.480 --> 20:16.681
if our governments
screw up our money.

20:16.683 --> 20:18.916
You know, Zimbabwe's
a good example

20:18.918 --> 20:23.254
of a government that lost
the trust of their people,

20:23.256 --> 20:24.522
and they lost
the trust of their people

20:24.524 --> 20:25.756
by printing too much money

20:25.758 --> 20:28.659
and causing runaway
hyperinflation.

20:28.661 --> 20:31.462
So I think you will see people
in other parts of the world

20:31.464 --> 20:33.264
who've experienced
hyperinflation

20:33.266 --> 20:35.466
who've experienced
bank failures.

20:35.468 --> 20:37.335
I think those will be
the kind of people

20:37.337 --> 20:41.505
who are looking for something...
Something new, right?

20:41.507 --> 20:43.808
They're willing
to take the risk.

20:43.810 --> 20:46.911
A lot of us
take the capacity
to send money to others,

20:46.913 --> 20:48.479
receive money, store money

20:48.481 --> 20:51.015
and do it electronically
these days for granted

20:51.017 --> 20:54.352
because we are amongst
the lucky 50% or so
of the world

20:54.354 --> 20:55.786
that have bank accounts.

20:55.788 --> 20:58.589
But 2.5 billion adults
in the world

20:58.591 --> 21:00.625
do not have access
to bank accounts.

21:00.627 --> 21:03.027
A technology like bitcoin,
cryptocurrency,

21:03.029 --> 21:08.366
has the capacity
to bring those people
into the financial system,

21:08.368 --> 21:10.434
to give them this power
to effectively have

21:10.436 --> 21:12.803
what you could argue
is a bank in their cell phone,

21:12.805 --> 21:14.472
a bank in their pocket.

21:14.474 --> 21:18.776
Really could open up commerce
to a lot of people

21:18.778 --> 21:21.579
who are currently
excluded from it.

21:21.581 --> 21:25.483
Somebody who is maybe
working in one country

21:25.485 --> 21:28.452
and, you know, they want
to send money back home.

21:28.454 --> 21:31.689
And right now,
like, western union
is a big way

21:31.691 --> 21:33.557
that people do remittances.

21:33.559 --> 21:35.526
From a western union
perspective,

21:35.528 --> 21:38.329
we serve clients in many
different locations
around the globe,

21:38.331 --> 21:39.930
and primarily for remittances.

21:39.932 --> 21:42.967
Western union
serves typically
an unbanked customer,

21:42.969 --> 21:46.604
a customer who is
either a migrant worker,

21:46.606 --> 21:48.939
or an individual who doesn't
feel comfortable

21:48.941 --> 21:50.641
in the financial services
sector.

21:50.643 --> 21:52.743
And the problem with remittances

21:52.745 --> 21:54.645
is they're really expensive.

21:54.647 --> 21:57.415
So if I'm sending $100
back home,

21:57.417 --> 22:00.351
I may end up spending
$5.00 or $10.00

22:00.353 --> 22:05.022
just on fees
to get that money
back to my family.

22:05.024 --> 22:07.892
That's a huge percentage
if you're poor and working.

22:07.894 --> 22:11.095
So since bitcoin
doesn't care about borders,

22:11.097 --> 22:13.464
I could just send bitcoin
to another country,

22:13.466 --> 22:15.766
and if my family
in that other country

22:15.768 --> 22:17.101
has some way of spending
that bitcoin

22:17.103 --> 22:18.736
or has some way of trans...

22:18.738 --> 22:21.839
Of exchanging that bitcoin
into the local currency,

22:21.841 --> 22:26.444
then it's just
quicker and cheaper
and more convenient.

22:26.446 --> 22:28.479
And a lot of people think
that remittances

22:28.481 --> 22:31.415
will be one of the really big
first uses for bitcoin.

22:32.551 --> 22:35.486
The one challenge there
is we deal with

22:35.488 --> 22:39.123
you know, at our company,
750 transactions, peak,
a second.

22:39.125 --> 22:41.092
And those happen instantly.

22:41.094 --> 22:43.794
If you look at a blockchain,
you have to wait
for verifications,

22:43.796 --> 22:45.463
and if you do a recent test,

22:45.465 --> 22:47.631
it takes about 15 minutes
for every transaction

22:47.633 --> 22:49.667
to be validated by the network.

22:49.669 --> 22:51.135
That doesn't scale,

22:51.137 --> 22:53.137
so it has
its challenges as well.

23:00.746 --> 23:03.547
Wikileaks, which solicits
and publishes

23:03.549 --> 23:05.383
secrets and suppressed material

23:05.385 --> 23:07.485
from whistleblowers
around the world,

23:07.487 --> 23:09.587
has been under cyber attack
from governments

23:09.589 --> 23:10.955
that want to shut it down.

23:10.957 --> 23:12.757
PayPal is the latest business

23:12.759 --> 23:14.592
to break ties with wikileaks,

23:14.594 --> 23:16.494
but the whistle-blowing
website

23:16.496 --> 23:19.029
dedicated to
publishing classified
government documents

23:19.031 --> 23:20.865
still continues to seek funding,

23:20.867 --> 23:24.402
while crossing out PayPal
as one method of payment.

23:24.404 --> 23:27.438
In order to insure
our future survival,

23:27.440 --> 23:30.875
wikileaks is now forced
to temporarily suspend

23:30.877 --> 23:33.144
all publishing operations

23:33.146 --> 23:36.714
in order to direct
all our resources

23:36.716 --> 23:40.751
into fighting the blockade
and raising funds.

23:40.753 --> 23:43.421
The wikileaks scandal
seemed to provide

23:43.423 --> 23:44.989
an opportunity for bitcoin.

23:44.991 --> 23:47.825
At the time,
the big banks and credit cards

23:47.827 --> 23:50.528
stopped processing payments
for wikileaks,

23:50.530 --> 23:53.697
and some people thought that
bitcoin would provide a way

23:53.699 --> 23:57.601
to send donations to wikileaks.

24:04.943 --> 24:09.213
You could certainly
see in the hubbub
around wikileaks

24:09.215 --> 24:11.715
that satoshi was still somebody

24:11.717 --> 24:14.885
who was very paranoid
about the government,

24:14.887 --> 24:18.088
and the government coming in
and taking too close a look

24:18.090 --> 24:19.557
at the bitcoin project.

24:19.559 --> 24:21.225
And you could also see
that satoshi,

24:21.227 --> 24:22.993
I think, realized at this point

24:22.995 --> 24:26.997
that bitcoin was still
young software

24:26.999 --> 24:29.700
and the kinks hadn't been
worked out yet.

24:29.702 --> 24:31.969
In, I think, late 2010,

24:31.971 --> 24:35.172
he asked me if it'd be okay
if he put my email address

24:35.174 --> 24:37.007
on the bitcoin. Org
home page,

24:37.009 --> 24:40.744
'cause he had been
the primary contact
for people.

24:40.746 --> 24:42.580
And I said, "sure."

24:42.582 --> 24:44.682
He went ahead
and changed the web page,

24:44.684 --> 24:47.685
but what he did is
he left his name there,

24:47.687 --> 24:50.521
but he took away
his email address.

24:50.523 --> 24:53.557
And so it was just me
and my email address

24:53.559 --> 24:56.694
who was suddenly getting
all of the attention.

24:56.696 --> 24:59.530
I think that was satoshi's way
of kind of saying,

24:59.532 --> 25:01.832
"you're the leader
of the project now."

25:01.834 --> 25:04.168
There was one particular email

25:04.170 --> 25:06.537
where he told me
that he was gonna step away
from the project

25:06.539 --> 25:08.939
and do something else.
He never told me what else

25:08.941 --> 25:11.775
he's gonna do
or that he is doing.

25:11.777 --> 25:15.980
I had just been invited
to give a talk at the CIA.

25:15.982 --> 25:17.815
And I told satoshi that
i accepted the invitation

25:17.817 --> 25:20.217
to go speak at the CIA.

25:20.219 --> 25:22.953
After he sent
that email to satoshi

25:22.955 --> 25:25.756
telling him
that he was planning
on going to the CIA,

25:25.758 --> 25:27.858
he never heard
from satoshi again,

25:27.860 --> 25:32.663
and that was
essentially the last time
anybody heard from satoshi.

25:32.665 --> 25:35.132
You very quickly get caught up
in the question

25:35.134 --> 25:37.234
of who is satoshi nakamoto?

25:37.236 --> 25:39.570
Where did this come from?
Who is this person?

25:39.572 --> 25:40.971
I mean, this is the 2000s.

25:40.973 --> 25:42.273
Information is out there,
everything.

25:42.275 --> 25:44.108
Everyone knows everything
about everybody.

25:44.110 --> 25:45.809
How can there possibly
be a person

25:45.811 --> 25:47.811
that nobody knows
who this guy is?

25:47.813 --> 25:50.948
But there is a person...
At least I think it's a person.

25:50.950 --> 25:52.216
It might be a group...

25:52.218 --> 25:53.851
Who nobody knows
who this guy is.

25:53.853 --> 25:58.188
And he kind of appears
out of nowhere in 2008

25:58.190 --> 26:00.257
on these cryptography
email lists,

26:00.259 --> 26:02.192
with this system called bitcoin.

26:02.194 --> 26:04.161
He's very active
in the early years,

26:04.163 --> 26:05.596
there's a lot of back and forth

26:05.598 --> 26:07.598
with him communicating
with people.

26:07.600 --> 26:10.100
It seemed like most people
kind of wrote him off

26:10.102 --> 26:13.237
as kind of like
a delusions-of-grandeur
kind of scheme.

26:13.239 --> 26:15.039
Hal Finney, on the other hand,

26:15.041 --> 26:18.275
seemed to be really interested
right from the beginning.

26:18.277 --> 26:20.077
He was a crypto-idealist.

26:20.079 --> 26:22.646
Like, he was not as
kind of cynical

26:22.648 --> 26:24.648
as many of the other cypherpunks

26:24.650 --> 26:25.950
so he got really into this.

26:25.952 --> 26:27.885
He started talking
to satoshi nakamoto,

26:27.887 --> 26:32.923
who he said seemed like
some young Japanese
American coder.

26:32.925 --> 26:37.161
Hal Finney was the first guy
to work with nakamoto.

26:37.163 --> 26:38.228
He was a cryptographer.

26:38.230 --> 26:39.863
Soon as nakamoto released it,

26:39.865 --> 26:41.865
he was one of the first people
to email him back and say,

26:41.867 --> 26:43.867
"hey, this is interesting.
I'd like to work with you."

26:43.869 --> 26:45.603
And in the first weeks
of bitcoin

26:45.605 --> 26:46.837
he worked with him
back and forth

26:46.839 --> 26:48.305
setting up the system.

26:48.307 --> 26:51.141
And satoshi nakamoto
ended up sending hal Finney

26:51.143 --> 26:54.244
the first ever bitcoin
transaction.

26:54.246 --> 26:57.147
Any discussion
of satoshi's identity

26:57.149 --> 27:00.184
has to go back to the fact
that bitcoin

27:00.186 --> 27:04.355
was based on this
small number of projects
back in the 1990s

27:04.357 --> 27:07.291
that only a handful
of people knew about,

27:07.293 --> 27:10.628
like hashcash
and bit gold and b money,

27:10.630 --> 27:15.065
and so you end up with
a pretty small group of people

27:15.067 --> 27:19.203
who would have known
about these projects.

27:19.205 --> 27:21.305
People though chaum,
David chaum, was, you know...

27:21.307 --> 27:22.940
Everybody in
the cypherpunk movement

27:22.942 --> 27:24.141
at one point or another,
they've said,

27:24.143 --> 27:25.843
"well, he must have been
satoshi."

27:25.845 --> 27:27.378
They've all come out
and denied it.

27:27.380 --> 27:29.380
Probably somebody
who started out in the '90s,

27:29.382 --> 27:31.181
in California,
with the cypherpunks.

27:31.183 --> 27:34.218
Somebody who was very,
very good at cryptography

27:34.220 --> 27:37.287
who understands encryption,
and has done a wonderful job

27:37.289 --> 27:42.092
of just separating bitcoin
from anything that can
identify him.

27:43.361 --> 27:45.396
I think for bitcoin's sake,

27:45.398 --> 27:48.332
that continuing anonymity
of satoshi

27:48.334 --> 27:51.235
has ended up being
a really good thing,

27:51.237 --> 27:54.905
because people who
have gotten involved in it

27:54.907 --> 27:59.076
have been able to write
their own ideas and dreams

27:59.078 --> 28:00.811
onto this technology,

28:00.813 --> 28:02.746
and there was nobody
there to say,

28:02.748 --> 28:04.748
"no, that's not
what I meant."

28:10.355 --> 28:11.922
In the early, early days,

28:11.924 --> 28:13.991
the first group was
really just a bunch of

28:13.993 --> 28:17.861
more or less
tech-minded coders.

28:41.820 --> 28:43.253
Then you had the libertarians
come on board,

28:43.255 --> 28:45.022
who saw it through
a political lens,

28:45.024 --> 28:47.491
I'm excited to be
a little bit of a part of it

28:47.493 --> 28:50.427
with allowing
and accepting bitcoin.

28:50.429 --> 28:52.863
And then you had these
two groups working together

28:52.865 --> 28:54.364
and they overlapped too,

28:54.366 --> 28:56.300
and the timing was very good

28:56.302 --> 28:59.436
because the existing system
was in utter disrepair.

28:59.438 --> 29:01.805
It was like a match
to a pile of wood

29:01.807 --> 29:03.407
with gasoline
poured on top of it.

29:03.409 --> 29:06.810
And the whole thing kind of
really goes viral and takes off,

29:06.812 --> 29:11.048
and then you have the suits,
the vc money,

29:11.050 --> 29:12.449
and it was very small at first,

29:12.451 --> 29:14.418
just a couple of guys
out in silicon valley

29:14.420 --> 29:18.055
who ran into bitcoin guys
at coffee houses

29:18.057 --> 29:20.390
and you started having
this meshing of conversations.

29:20.392 --> 29:22.426
Once silicon valley
gets on board,

29:22.428 --> 29:25.095
that whole dynamic
starts to take off.

29:25.097 --> 29:27.331
So now you have
the tech-minded coders,

29:27.333 --> 29:29.433
the libertarians,
the counter-culture people,

29:29.435 --> 29:30.968
the vc, silicon valley,

29:30.970 --> 29:34.104
and you have this entire
great mishmash of people

29:34.106 --> 29:35.372
coming together.

29:35.374 --> 29:37.040
You had a network effect.

29:37.042 --> 29:38.442
The more people
that got involved,

29:38.444 --> 29:40.444
the stronger the network got,

29:40.446 --> 29:43.380
and the more it grew
and it really started growing
on itself.

29:43.382 --> 29:46.550
And in 2013 especially,

29:46.552 --> 29:49.853
you literally see
this thing mushroom.

29:49.855 --> 29:52.890
The thing was just growing,
growing and growing
and growing

29:52.892 --> 29:55.292
as more and more people
got involved.

29:58.396 --> 30:02.065
I think most bitcoin
companies at the time

30:02.067 --> 30:06.236
knew that a big part
of the market for bitcoins

30:06.238 --> 30:09.206
was people buying drugs
on silk road

30:09.208 --> 30:11.041
who needed bitcoins to do that.

30:11.043 --> 30:12.910
The big bang moment for bitcoin

30:12.912 --> 30:14.378
was the silk road.

30:14.380 --> 30:17.848
What Ross ulbricht did
by creating the silk road

30:17.850 --> 30:21.185
was he took this
by no means common

30:21.187 --> 30:23.387
but usable cryptocurrency
called bitcoin

30:23.389 --> 30:25.522
and he married it
with a streamlined,

30:25.524 --> 30:27.391
workable user interface

30:27.393 --> 30:30.861
that was a free market
that could sell anything.

30:32.397 --> 30:35.332
What would happen
if people were really free

30:35.334 --> 30:38.135
truly free to trade
what they wanted to?

30:38.137 --> 30:42.139
Ross did have
an extremely radical

30:42.141 --> 30:44.541
libertarian viewpoint,

30:44.543 --> 30:48.145
and really wanted to experiment
with using technology

30:48.147 --> 30:51.281
to create free markets
for people.

30:51.283 --> 30:54.885
What Ross ulbricht
did is a combination
of Tor and bitcoin.

30:54.887 --> 30:57.187
That was the "aha" moment
that Ross must have had.

30:57.189 --> 31:00.624
The silk road was
basically the fruition

31:00.626 --> 31:05.929
of all the cypherpunk dreams,
the crypto-anarchists'
utopia

31:05.931 --> 31:07.865
that they had imagined
in the '90s,

31:07.867 --> 31:09.399
you know, was real now.

31:09.401 --> 31:14.371
This was a perfectly,
in theory, anonymous website,

31:14.373 --> 31:16.607
with perfectly, in theory,
anonymous money

31:16.609 --> 31:19.243
used to by any contrabands
imaginable.

31:19.245 --> 31:23.113
The silk road website
is a particular headache
for authorities.

31:23.115 --> 31:25.582
It's a anonymous
online marketplace

31:25.584 --> 31:28.485
where people sell drugs
that are posted to customers

31:28.487 --> 31:31.154
all over the world.

31:31.156 --> 31:33.323
Cyber investigators, you know,
when there's a crime

31:33.325 --> 31:36.126
can kind of trace you back
because you have an ip address.

31:36.128 --> 31:37.227
It's like a telephone number,

31:37.229 --> 31:38.929
so if you call another computer

31:38.931 --> 31:41.164
that ip address is tracked.

31:41.166 --> 31:43.433
On Tor, that's taken away,
because your information

31:43.435 --> 31:45.402
hops from computer
to computer to computer

31:45.404 --> 31:47.471
so there's no way
to trace you back
to your original one.

31:47.473 --> 31:52.109
Tor is an anonymous system,

31:52.111 --> 31:54.177
so if you use the Tor browser,

31:54.179 --> 31:55.612
which it has a browser.

31:55.614 --> 31:57.414
You can go to Tor
and download their browser,

31:57.416 --> 32:01.051
you can browse with
some degree of security.

32:01.053 --> 32:04.054
So that's great for plugging
your banking information

32:04.056 --> 32:05.522
into a site
so you don't get hacked.

32:05.524 --> 32:08.659
The other component of Tor,
which has similar uses,

32:08.661 --> 32:10.360
is called Tor hidden services.

32:10.362 --> 32:14.164
Tor hidden services
is actually, to put it simply,

32:14.166 --> 32:16.199
a url that doesn't have ".Com"
on the end of it.

32:16.201 --> 32:17.534
It has ".Onion."

32:17.536 --> 32:19.403
And that is its own little space

32:19.405 --> 32:23.974
where you can create websites
and you could freely transact

32:23.976 --> 32:26.610
without oversight or regulation.

32:26.612 --> 32:28.645
People put websites on there

32:28.647 --> 32:31.148
that are outside of
law enforcement's view.

32:31.150 --> 32:33.083
There's hackers for hire,
there's malware,

32:33.085 --> 32:35.118
there's credit card
dump services

32:35.120 --> 32:36.553
there's a whole bunch of them.

32:36.555 --> 32:39.589
Chris tarbell has ended up
being, in some ways,

32:39.591 --> 32:43.527
the most important
FBI digital crime investigator

32:43.529 --> 32:45.195
of the last few years.

32:45.197 --> 32:48.031
He was the one who took
down anonymous, essentially.

32:48.033 --> 32:51.168
So we decided
to start looking at some
of the services on Tor,

32:51.170 --> 32:52.469
and silk road being one them,

32:52.471 --> 32:54.171
other cases, they would hit Tor,

32:54.173 --> 32:55.973
and they would kind of throw
their hands in the air

32:55.975 --> 32:58.575
and say "it's Tor, there's not
much we can do about it."

32:58.577 --> 33:02.112
I found it interesting
to kind of take a look at it
and tackle it.

33:07.552 --> 33:09.119
Bitinstant was basically born

33:09.121 --> 33:10.754
because if you wanted
to move your dollars

33:10.756 --> 33:12.122
into a bitcoin exchange,

33:12.124 --> 33:13.690
it takes at least three days.

33:13.692 --> 33:16.693
And since the major exchange,
mt. Gox, was in Tokyo

33:16.695 --> 33:18.495
it could take a week or more.

33:18.497 --> 33:20.597
So that's really problematic,

33:20.599 --> 33:23.200
and basically
Charlie figured out that

33:23.202 --> 33:27.304
if you just held a balance
of dollars at the exchange,

33:27.306 --> 33:30.073
you could go to him and say,
"Charlie, I'll give you $100.

33:30.075 --> 33:33.110
Will you give me $100
of credit at the exchange?"

33:33.112 --> 33:35.445
And you can literally
then have your dollars
at the exchange

33:35.447 --> 33:38.415
in ten seconds
as opposed to a week.

33:38.417 --> 33:41.284
So that's hugely helpful,
especially when bitcoin
is so volatile

33:41.286 --> 33:43.353
and you need
to know exactly what price
you're going to get.

33:43.355 --> 33:45.022
Charlie was raising capital

33:45.024 --> 33:47.090
right as, sort of, i joined.

33:47.092 --> 33:49.626
During that process,
he came across lots of

33:49.628 --> 33:52.329
interested investors who were
starting to get a whiff

33:52.331 --> 33:56.133
that maybe this
bitcoin thing was cool.

33:56.135 --> 33:58.035
We had an interesting
debate early on

33:58.037 --> 34:01.405
about do we invest in bitcoin
or bitcoin companies

34:01.407 --> 34:04.241
and we sort of
decided to do both.

34:04.243 --> 34:07.077
More towards investing
in actually bitcoin

34:07.079 --> 34:08.545
in the asset early days,

34:08.547 --> 34:11.481
but also trying to place
a few bets in the ecosystem

34:11.483 --> 34:15.152
to support the companies,
support the entrepreneurs,

34:15.154 --> 34:17.420
and see how that went.

34:17.422 --> 34:21.091
A few days after they first
found out about bitcoin,

34:21.092 --> 34:24.527
they were in the bitinstant
offices in New York

34:24.530 --> 34:26.563
meeting with Erik and Charlie.

34:26.565 --> 34:31.835
And Erik and Charlie
essentially talked them
through bitcoin

34:31.837 --> 34:35.539
and answered all of their
questions and concerns.

34:35.541 --> 34:38.241
What made you invest
in bitinstant?

34:38.243 --> 34:41.610
There are a lot of companies
and exchanges and websites.

34:41.612 --> 34:45.315
With respect to bitcoin,
regulation is obviously
a big question.

34:45.317 --> 34:48.385
What you do want is
a company that sort of takes
that seriously

34:48.387 --> 34:50.853
and understands that
there's the technology element,

34:50.856 --> 34:52.422
there's building the company,

34:52.424 --> 34:53.489
and then there's also
creating the company

34:53.492 --> 34:54.791
that works with regulators.

34:54.793 --> 34:56.525
And so that's bitinstant.

34:56.527 --> 34:58.795
It's not this sort of
completely underground thing?

34:58.797 --> 35:02.299
Yeah, Charlie the ceo
happens to have been in
this space for a long time,

35:02.301 --> 35:04.801
so he's sort of on
the pulse and the cutting edge.

35:04.803 --> 35:06.470
You know, you come out
and you say, like,

35:06.472 --> 35:08.338
"we want this bitcoin thing
to overturn everything,"

35:08.340 --> 35:10.407
but at the same time
we have to be compliant

35:10.409 --> 35:12.209
and you have to know
your customer.

35:12.211 --> 35:14.878
You have to know
every single customer
no matter what.

35:14.880 --> 35:17.280
Even if they're transferring
a dollar or $1,000.

35:17.282 --> 35:18.782
And how reasonable is that?

35:18.784 --> 35:20.750
The term "money laundering"
was invented by banks,

35:20.752 --> 35:22.552
and knowing your customer
shouldn't be

35:22.554 --> 35:24.688
this complicated,
expensive thing.

35:24.690 --> 35:27.791
And you shouldn't
treat everyone like
a criminal in the beginning.

35:27.793 --> 35:29.759
They really wanted us involved.

35:29.761 --> 35:32.529
People were really friendly,
because it benefits you

35:32.531 --> 35:34.631
to onboard more people in,

35:34.633 --> 35:37.834
so bitcoin's always been
this very friendly community

35:37.836 --> 35:41.371
and it's also... in some ways
it's self-serving that way,

35:41.373 --> 35:45.142
but we were there
for the right reasons.

35:45.144 --> 35:48.411
At the time, bitinstant
was the big company

35:48.413 --> 35:49.746
other than mt. Gox.

35:49.748 --> 35:53.416
It was the way that most
Americans were able

35:53.418 --> 35:55.385
to buy bitcoins.

35:55.387 --> 35:57.521
Here it is.

35:57.523 --> 36:00.190
So bitinstant
was located right there.

36:00.192 --> 36:02.726
I think it's the one
that now says "bling."

36:02.728 --> 36:04.828
It was a whirlwind six months.

36:04.830 --> 36:07.664
Going from total obscurity
with no money

36:07.666 --> 36:11.635
to becoming one of
the hot startups of bitcoin.

36:11.637 --> 36:15.605
But almost as soon as
the twins made their investment
in the company,

36:15.607 --> 36:17.207
it began falling apart.

36:17.209 --> 36:19.476
The twins had a much more
practical approach

36:19.478 --> 36:21.311
to bitcoin and bitinstant.

36:21.313 --> 36:24.281
They wanted to see
the company making money

36:24.283 --> 36:26.283
and making as much money
as it could

36:26.285 --> 36:27.717
as quickly as it could.

36:27.719 --> 36:30.587
They saw early on
that it would be regulated,

36:30.589 --> 36:32.222
that it wasn't
gonna be this big,

36:32.224 --> 36:34.758
and have no one be
interested in regulating it.

36:34.760 --> 36:37.594
So they feared that
all kinds of regulators

36:37.596 --> 36:39.696
would come in
at all different angles

36:39.698 --> 36:41.565
and tie the thing up
in a complete morass

36:41.567 --> 36:43.200
where nothing
would ever get done.

36:43.202 --> 36:46.603
So they wanted to help
drive the regulation

36:46.605 --> 36:49.339
so that whatever regulation
would be there would work

36:49.341 --> 36:53.376
and would not end up
being a complete dead end
for bitcoin.

36:54.579 --> 36:56.947
That strategy is smarter,

36:56.949 --> 36:58.915
from purely
a business perspective,

36:58.917 --> 37:01.585
but I'm not in this purely
from a business perspective.

37:01.587 --> 37:04.354
I am in this for business
and because I'm trying

37:04.356 --> 37:05.755
to change the world
and make it better,

37:05.757 --> 37:07.824
and building bitcoin companies

37:07.826 --> 37:09.392
and begging for regulation

37:09.394 --> 37:11.228
that matches exactly
the banking regulation

37:11.230 --> 37:12.696
that has caused so many problems

37:12.698 --> 37:14.731
I feel like is
counterproductive.

37:14.733 --> 37:19.569
For the most part,
bitinstant was actually
taking steps

37:19.571 --> 37:24.874
to make sure that people
weren't using the service
for illegal purposes,

37:24.876 --> 37:28.478
but Charlie made the mistake
in dealing with btcking

37:28.480 --> 37:30.814
of acknowledging that he knew

37:30.816 --> 37:33.016
what btcking was doing,

37:33.018 --> 37:35.919
and that he was acquiring
bitcoins to sell them

37:35.921 --> 37:37.621
to silk road customers.

37:39.890 --> 37:42.959
In this case,
Charlie worked with the guy

37:42.961 --> 37:46.296
and wrote emails that
essentially acknowledged

37:46.298 --> 37:48.965
he knew what this guy was up to.

38:10.354 --> 38:11.855
That stunning arrest
of the drug kingpin

38:11.857 --> 38:13.890
who goes by the name
"dread pirate Roberts"

38:13.892 --> 38:16.426
and appears to have cornered
the Internet drug market.

38:16.428 --> 38:19.062
His real name is Ross ulbricht
and his website, silk road,

38:19.064 --> 38:21.898
is packed with products
like cocaine and heroin.

38:21.900 --> 38:23.867
The payment system
is all through bitcoins,

38:23.869 --> 38:26.403
which is basically
digital currency,

38:26.405 --> 38:28.705
not backed up by
any international banks,

38:28.707 --> 38:30.473
not backed up by any us banks,

38:30.475 --> 38:33.043
but simply based on
the confidence of the users

38:33.045 --> 38:35.612
who exchange these bitcoins
computer to computer.

38:40.484 --> 38:42.519
There's a reason why
the case was tried in New York,

38:42.521 --> 38:43.820
in the Southern district,

38:43.822 --> 38:47.924
and largely that
was because of bitcoin.

38:47.926 --> 38:50.060
Ross was caught
in San Francisco.

38:50.062 --> 38:53.563
The silk road servers
were out of the country.

38:53.565 --> 38:56.766
So why was Ross's case
tried in the Southern district
of New York

38:56.768 --> 39:00.804
where most of the financial
regulations cases
are dealt with?

39:00.806 --> 39:03.039
Where the district attorney,
preet bharara

39:03.041 --> 39:04.974
has been all over bitcoin.

39:04.976 --> 39:07.544
Where Charles schumer,
the senator, has been all over
bitcoin.

39:07.546 --> 39:09.979
Ross ulbricht's case
is a bitcoin case.

39:09.981 --> 39:11.648
There's absolutely
no denying it.

39:11.650 --> 39:14.718
The level of threat
that the silk road posed

39:14.720 --> 39:16.853
to the marketplace,
to wall street,

39:16.855 --> 39:19.589
whether it's a perceived threat
or an actual threat,

39:19.591 --> 39:21.524
was humongous.

39:21.526 --> 39:25.628
And the idea that somebody
could create a marketplace

39:25.630 --> 39:29.733
where you could
freely transact without
oversight or regulation

39:29.735 --> 39:34.037
had to be dealt
a massive and public blow.

39:34.039 --> 39:39.676
Bitcoin kind of monetized
that anonymous part
of the Internet

39:39.678 --> 39:41.811
and made it possible
to trade in things

39:41.813 --> 39:45.415
that the federal government
doesn't want you to trade in.

39:45.417 --> 39:47.417
Law enforcement moves slowly

39:47.419 --> 39:50.120
but it's a big heavy wheel
that grinds finely,

39:50.122 --> 39:52.956
so, you know, someone
was running a hidden service,

39:52.958 --> 39:54.891
and now they're
in prison for life.

39:54.893 --> 39:57.160
They were playing hardball.
It was very evident

39:57.162 --> 40:02.031
that their intention,
as the judge herself said
in her sentencing,

40:02.033 --> 40:03.800
was to make an example
out of Ross,

40:03.802 --> 40:06.836
was to say to all of you
people using bitcoin,

40:06.838 --> 40:08.805
to all of you people
who want to tangle

40:08.807 --> 40:12.909
with unregulated marketplaces
and technologies

40:12.911 --> 40:15.178
and open source
cryptocurrencies,

40:15.180 --> 40:19.983
"we will throw the book
in its entirety at you
if you do this."

40:19.985 --> 40:21.985
We seized a whole bunch
of bitcoins.

40:21.987 --> 40:26.189
And in order to sell
those bitcoins off
or go to an exchange,

40:26.191 --> 40:29.559
you have to fit within
federal law and state law.

40:29.561 --> 40:31.127
There's not really an exchange
that could handle that,

40:31.129 --> 40:33.963
that met those regulations
at the current time,

40:33.965 --> 40:35.865
so it had to be handled
through auction.

40:47.044 --> 40:48.912
You know anything
about bitcoins?

40:48.914 --> 40:53.583
There's an article
in "the wall street journal"
today

40:53.585 --> 40:56.052
- on bitcoins.
- - Really?

40:56.054 --> 40:58.154
Right here,
if you want to read it.

40:58.156 --> 41:00.690
It is?

41:00.692 --> 41:02.125
Digital currency,
did you see that?

41:02.127 --> 41:04.160
Wow, oh!

41:04.162 --> 41:06.930
"Digital currencies
will disrupt global finance,

41:06.932 --> 41:08.965
transform the way
we pay for things,

41:08.967 --> 41:12.469
and just maybe,
make the world a fairer place."

41:12.471 --> 41:14.037
From what I've read
on the computer,

41:14.039 --> 41:15.638
they have had some problems.

41:18.476 --> 41:20.710
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

41:20.712 --> 41:23.146
The reason is
because you can't track it.

41:23.148 --> 41:26.583
Well, I think I don't like
this idea at all.

41:31.555 --> 41:33.089
When we saw
the silk road shut down,

41:33.091 --> 41:34.824
a lot of people said,

41:34.826 --> 41:37.160
"bitcoin's nothing but
illegal drugs on the Internet.

41:37.162 --> 41:38.828
That's what it is."

41:38.830 --> 41:40.597
And they would point
at the silk road and say,

41:40.599 --> 41:42.966
"look here
at all the stuff
that's happening here."

41:42.968 --> 41:46.269
And I think when you saw
the silk road shut down

41:46.271 --> 41:48.204
and bitcoin transaction volume

41:48.206 --> 41:50.573
take a tiny little dip,

41:50.575 --> 41:52.742
and then keep going up,

41:52.744 --> 41:55.211
you know, I think that was
a great event to point at

41:55.213 --> 41:58.948
and say, "it really
wasn't about that.

41:58.950 --> 42:00.917
It really isn't about that."

42:00.919 --> 42:03.052
It's a tiny little part
of the economy.

42:09.026 --> 42:10.727
I guess in the last week

42:10.729 --> 42:13.563
I've really started
hearing about bitcoin.

42:13.565 --> 42:15.131
Recently I heard a scenario

42:15.133 --> 42:17.934
after the FBI had seized
a bunch of bitcoins

42:17.936 --> 42:19.802
due to illegal transactions,

42:19.804 --> 42:21.137
now they're gonna be
auctioning them off

42:21.139 --> 42:23.606
like they would a private yacht

42:23.608 --> 42:26.042
for, you know,
from some drug dealer.

42:26.044 --> 42:30.146
So that, in a way,
legitimizes the use of it

42:30.148 --> 42:32.215
as a currency.

42:37.021 --> 42:41.891
Looks like it's the first live

42:41.893 --> 42:45.562
bitcoin exchange on wall street.

42:45.564 --> 42:47.096
Looks that way.

