Yeah, so one for 950.

42:50.669 --> 42:52.569
- Buying or selling?
- -Selling.

42:52.571 --> 42:54.237
550 on a thousand...

42:54.239 --> 42:58.207
Right now we were looking
at the open interest

42:58.209 --> 43:00.777
at the floor of
the bitcoin exchange.

43:00.779 --> 43:03.980
There's different
exchanges that are online,

43:03.982 --> 43:05.348
that will present
at the bidding house,

43:05.350 --> 43:09.586
but there's no true
open outcry exchange.

43:09.588 --> 43:11.187
Buyers and sellers
coming together

43:11.189 --> 43:14.791
in an open, clear,
transparent, honest way.

43:16.627 --> 43:19.162
- Gox is the highest one.
- Why don't we call it 900?

43:19.164 --> 43:20.630
900...

43:25.936 --> 43:27.337
There's my transaction,

43:27.339 --> 43:29.305
probably the first two
transactions of the day.

43:29.307 --> 43:30.707
It's really not about the money,

43:30.709 --> 43:32.275
it's about being involved,

43:32.277 --> 43:34.397
and I think there's a lot
more people gonna follow me.

43:40.150 --> 43:42.151
Charlie shrem, 24 years old,

43:42.153 --> 43:44.621
arrested today
and charged with engaging
in money laundering

43:44.623 --> 43:48.024
shrem enabled people
to transfer money

43:48.026 --> 43:50.960
from bitcoin to cash
via his company
called bitinstant.

43:50.962 --> 43:52.762
Now the other point
that the DEA is making

43:52.764 --> 43:56.265
is that shrem bought drugs
online at silk road

43:56.267 --> 44:00.303
and that he knew silk road
was a trafficking website.

44:00.305 --> 44:02.705
And we know the winklevoss twins

44:02.707 --> 44:05.875
who obviously were featured
in the movie about Facebook.

44:05.877 --> 44:09.045
They're actually investors
in shrem's company.

44:09.047 --> 44:12.815
Yeah, you know,
a lot of people are very
excited by this idea.

44:12.817 --> 44:15.184
They like the idea that
you can have a currency

44:15.186 --> 44:17.887
that is not tied
to any kind of central bank,

44:17.889 --> 44:19.722
but at the same time,
i mean, think about it.

44:19.724 --> 44:21.024
If you're in
the federal government,

44:21.026 --> 44:22.659
you don't like the idea
that people could

44:22.661 --> 44:25.294
effectively use another
form of cash

44:25.296 --> 44:29.232
to buy things that they
shouldn't be buying online.

44:29.234 --> 44:32.335
With me, it wasn't all
my customers.

44:32.337 --> 44:34.070
It was one customer,

44:34.072 --> 44:36.406
out of about 100,000 customers.

44:36.408 --> 44:38.775
This was one customer.
One single...

44:38.777 --> 44:40.143
And I made that case
in my sentencing.

44:40.145 --> 44:42.679
I said, "your honor,
this was one customer."

44:42.681 --> 44:46.282
It happened that I was literally
coming home from Amsterdam.

44:46.284 --> 44:47.884
I was in my sweatshirt.
I was still stoned.

44:47.886 --> 44:49.118
I didn't know what was going on.

44:49.120 --> 44:51.821
Charlie did not know
when to shut up,

44:51.823 --> 44:54.957
and that ended up
getting him in trouble,

44:54.959 --> 44:57.927
and probably led to the end
of his company.

44:57.929 --> 44:59.262
But they got me under
the patriot act,

44:59.264 --> 45:00.830
and it's money laundering

45:00.832 --> 45:03.132
because I knew that
the money I was taking

45:03.134 --> 45:07.036
was eventually possibly
going to be used for drug
trafficking.

45:07.038 --> 45:09.772
Now drug trafficking
is not buying drugs,
it's selling drugs.

45:09.774 --> 45:11.274
I didn't help the drug seller.

45:11.276 --> 45:13.009
I helped the guy buy drugs.

45:13.011 --> 45:15.745
But I never went
to trial because...

45:15.747 --> 45:19.482
And I pled guilty because
who wins at trial, you know?

45:19.484 --> 45:22.318
Like this guy, silk road,
he's gonna go to life.

45:22.320 --> 45:24.220
In trial,
all he needed to get
was a lady

45:24.222 --> 45:26.723
whose son died
from a cocaine overdose

45:26.725 --> 45:29.792
and I would've...
the jury would've convicted me
right there.

45:29.794 --> 45:32.128
So essentially Charlie was
selling bitcoins to a guy

45:32.130 --> 45:33.996
who was selling
bitcoins to people

45:33.998 --> 45:37.433
who were putting drugs
into their own bodies.

45:37.435 --> 45:40.169
And for this,
Charlie was charged
with crimes

45:40.171 --> 45:43.106
that could've put him
in jail for 20 years.

45:43.108 --> 45:44.941
That's what the prosecutors
were shooting for.

45:44.943 --> 45:47.910
We have banks that have atms

45:47.912 --> 45:49.412
on every street corner
in America,

45:49.414 --> 45:51.748
and those banks know very well

45:51.750 --> 45:53.216
that that cash
is getting used for drugs.

45:53.218 --> 45:54.884
And yet, that's fine.

45:54.886 --> 45:56.786
They're allowed to do that.
No one gets in trouble.

45:56.788 --> 45:58.988
But Charlie sells bitcoin
to a guy who sells bitcoin

45:58.990 --> 46:01.224
to someone who uses drugs,
and he goes to jail.

46:01.226 --> 46:04.494
He was an entrepreneur that
started building this industry,

46:04.496 --> 46:07.096
built services
that people found useful,

46:07.098 --> 46:09.265
when bankers almost destroyed
the world economy

46:09.267 --> 46:12.869
and none of them
got in trouble whatsoever.

46:12.871 --> 46:15.404
And here we have this
23-year-old kid,
he goes to jail

46:15.406 --> 46:18.207
because he started
building an alternative.

46:27.885 --> 46:29.385
Over the last six months,

46:29.387 --> 46:32.321
our agency has been conducting
an extensive inquiry

46:32.323 --> 46:35.892
into virtual currency.

46:35.894 --> 46:37.827
The information
we're going to gather

46:37.829 --> 46:39.796
in this fact-finding effort

46:39.798 --> 46:41.430
will allow us to put forward,

46:41.432 --> 46:44.000
during the course of 2014,

46:44.002 --> 46:46.369
a proposed regulatory framework

46:46.371 --> 46:50.373
for virtual currency firms
operating in New York.

46:50.375 --> 46:52.942
Yesterday, we had
serious criminal conduct

46:52.944 --> 46:55.812
come to light involving
virtual currency

46:55.814 --> 46:57.480
as a vehicle
for money laundering

46:57.482 --> 47:00.082
drug trafficking,
and other major felonies.

47:00.084 --> 47:03.419
Right now, the regulation
of virtual currency industry

47:03.421 --> 47:07.056
is still akin
to a virtual wild west.

47:07.058 --> 47:08.925
That's why we're evaluating

47:08.927 --> 47:10.426
whether our agency should issue

47:10.428 --> 47:12.295
a so-called bitlicense,

47:12.297 --> 47:15.298
specifically tailored
to virtual currencies.

47:15.300 --> 47:17.834
I think people who imagine

47:17.836 --> 47:20.837
a very powerful utility,
like bitcoin

47:20.839 --> 47:23.573
that would somehow escape
regulation entirely

47:23.575 --> 47:27.243
are either naive

47:27.245 --> 47:30.847
or extreme optimists.

47:30.849 --> 47:33.082
Bitcoin is a battle of ideas,

47:33.084 --> 47:35.518
and it forces the issue of
whether people should be

47:35.520 --> 47:38.487
as free in their handling
of money as they are

47:38.489 --> 47:40.523
in their handling
of speech or religion

47:40.525 --> 47:42.892
or relationships
with each other.

47:42.894 --> 47:45.962
If you want to have
this thing go mainstream,

47:45.964 --> 47:48.231
you're going to have
to have the regulators,

47:48.233 --> 47:49.932
the lawmakers weigh in on it.

47:49.934 --> 47:52.101
One of the first ones
who really took an interest

47:52.103 --> 47:53.636
was Benjamin lawsky.

47:53.638 --> 47:56.239
Very important regulator
in the financial world.

47:56.241 --> 47:59.508
And in January, 2014,
holds these public hearings

47:59.510 --> 48:01.878
because he wants
to come up with a license

48:01.880 --> 48:04.146
for bitcoin companies.

48:04.148 --> 48:06.082
We believe that putting in place

48:06.084 --> 48:08.651
appropriate
regulatory safeguards
for virtual currencies

48:08.653 --> 48:10.987
will ultimately be beneficial

48:10.989 --> 48:14.523
to the long-term strength
of the industry itself.

48:14.525 --> 48:17.560
Lawsky was essentially
given the opportunity

48:17.562 --> 48:22.265
to write the rules
for this whole new industry
from scratch.

48:22.267 --> 48:24.500
The first question
is the obvious one

48:24.502 --> 48:25.935
that's on everyone's mind.

48:25.937 --> 48:27.937
Sort of unexpected yesterday,

48:27.939 --> 48:30.172
but with the arrests
we saw obviously

48:30.174 --> 48:32.275
that's put a bit of a cloud

48:32.277 --> 48:34.043
hanging over
the industry right now,

48:34.045 --> 48:37.546
and so how do each of you react
to what we saw yesterday,

48:37.548 --> 48:41.417
what it means for bitcoin
or virtual currency
and its future?

48:41.419 --> 48:44.387
I think it further supports that

48:44.389 --> 48:46.389
bad guys are gonna do
bad things,

48:46.391 --> 48:49.025
and they're gonna
use whatever technology
is available to them.

48:49.027 --> 48:51.961
But I view it as,
if the allegations are true
and they're convicted,

48:51.963 --> 48:54.297
the system works.

48:54.299 --> 48:56.465
Are people still doing bad
things with bitcoin?

48:56.467 --> 49:00.102
Sure. Is the majority of
the bitcoin activity vice?

49:00.104 --> 49:01.270
Not a chance.

49:01.272 --> 49:02.571
So I think the issue you raise

49:02.573 --> 49:05.241
is one that people
like to write about,

49:05.243 --> 49:07.610
the media likes
to write about it,
makes great headlines.

49:07.612 --> 49:09.578
You get a lot of clicks.
You can sell a lot of ads,

49:09.580 --> 49:12.949
but I think
it's in the rearview mirror.

49:12.951 --> 49:15.584
There are some people
in the bitcoin community

49:15.586 --> 49:17.687
from the libertarian
side of things

49:17.689 --> 49:20.690
that want government
to just leave it alone.

49:20.692 --> 49:24.560
Would you say regulation
is both inevitable

49:24.562 --> 49:26.729
but more importantly,
actually ultimately

49:26.731 --> 49:29.665
going to be crucial
for the survival
of virtual currency?

49:29.667 --> 49:31.500
Sounds like a terrible
idea to me.

49:31.502 --> 49:33.135
Just understand what we're
trying to do with bitcoin.

49:33.137 --> 49:35.171
We're trying to create a world

49:35.173 --> 49:39.608
where transactions
can move globally for free,
okay?

49:39.610 --> 49:43.379
And making these companies hire

49:43.381 --> 49:45.614
you know, some outsourced
compliance firm

49:45.616 --> 49:47.583
is a bad idea.

49:47.585 --> 49:49.318
It'd be great, in any industry,

49:49.320 --> 49:51.153
if you could just
open the door and let folks

49:51.155 --> 49:52.688
run out and give it a shot.

49:52.690 --> 49:55.358
We may choose not
to invest in a company

49:55.360 --> 49:58.661
if they can't
get licensed by you.

49:58.663 --> 50:01.163
If the choice ultimately
is between

50:01.165 --> 50:03.532
preventing money laundering
on the one hand,

50:03.534 --> 50:06.102
and I probably
shouldn't even use the word
"money laundering"

50:06.104 --> 50:07.770
'cause it's too nice
a word, frankly.

50:07.772 --> 50:10.473
Money laundering
is the facilitation

50:10.475 --> 50:12.375
of all kinds of horrific crimes

50:12.377 --> 50:14.143
that I think
everyone in this room

50:14.145 --> 50:15.611
never wants to see happen.

50:15.613 --> 50:18.414
Acts of terrorism,
funding rogue nations, etc.,

50:18.416 --> 50:20.750
all take place through
massive money laundering.

50:20.752 --> 50:22.785
Now the choice
for the regulator is,

50:22.787 --> 50:25.187
permit money laundering
on the one hand,

50:25.189 --> 50:29.091
or permit innovation
on the other.

50:29.093 --> 50:31.227
We're always going to choose

50:31.229 --> 50:33.129
squelching
the money laundering first.

50:34.798 --> 50:38.768
I agree that I don't think
anybody wants money laundering.

50:38.770 --> 50:41.771
When we got a...
First saw bitcoin

50:41.773 --> 50:43.806
you know, about a year and
a half, almost two years ago.

50:43.808 --> 50:43.806
I don't think anybody would deny

50:43.808 --> 50:46.542
that it was a bit
of a wild, wild west,

50:46.544 --> 50:48.077
because there was no regulation.

50:48.079 --> 50:50.479
There was no framework
to evaluate

50:50.481 --> 50:52.715
the asset, evaluate companies,

50:52.717 --> 50:55.384
determine who was compliant
and who was not,

50:55.386 --> 50:57.787
and a wild west
attracts cowboys.

50:57.789 --> 51:00.823
And I don't think anybody here
would disagree with the fact

51:00.825 --> 51:03.626
that a sheriff
would be a good thing.

51:03.628 --> 51:05.261
A lot of, I think,
the entrepreneurs

51:05.263 --> 51:07.430
feel like they have
to self-censor.

51:07.432 --> 51:10.800
They don't want to come out
vocally critical
of the regulations.

51:10.802 --> 51:12.535
Part of that is maybe
'cause some of them

51:12.537 --> 51:13.736
just like regulations,

51:13.738 --> 51:15.304
but I think another part of it,

51:15.306 --> 51:17.706
some of them just feel like
they will get

51:17.708 --> 51:20.142
attention of the regulators
if they come out against them.

51:20.144 --> 51:22.278
Yes, we want them to innovate,
but at the same time,

51:22.280 --> 51:25.648
we just can't live in a world
where we're gonna permit

51:25.650 --> 51:27.450
money laundering to go on.

51:27.452 --> 51:29.251
I think regulators
should give bitcoin

51:29.253 --> 51:30.386
some time to grow up.

51:30.388 --> 51:32.254
Too much regulation now

51:32.256 --> 51:33.789
will just stifle innovation.

51:33.791 --> 51:37.093
I think before regulators
kind of come in and say,

51:37.095 --> 51:38.627
"we're gonna solve
all your problems,"

51:38.629 --> 51:41.130
and then fail
to solve all their problems,

51:41.132 --> 51:43.232
I think they should give
the innovators time

51:43.234 --> 51:45.201
to solve those problems.

51:45.203 --> 51:48.537
One function of regulation
is to make things clearer,

51:48.539 --> 51:51.207
so right now bitcoin,
because it's so new,

51:51.209 --> 51:54.510
is in a state of flux
everywhere.

51:54.512 --> 51:55.578
The lesson from the Internet

51:55.580 --> 51:57.713
is anything that China bans,

51:57.715 --> 51:58.715
invest in.

52:00.818 --> 52:04.420
And that's a joke,
but the U.S.

52:04.422 --> 52:07.590
Allows Google to operate here,
allows Twitter to operate here,

52:07.592 --> 52:08.891
allows bitcoin to operate here,

52:08.893 --> 52:11.193
allows Facebook to operate here.

52:11.195 --> 52:13.896
Chinese government
doesn't allow any of those
companies to operate

52:13.898 --> 52:18.434
the way they operate
in this country,
or at all.

52:18.436 --> 52:20.503
This is about freedom,
ultimately.

52:20.505 --> 52:22.838
You know, we're 50 yards

52:22.840 --> 52:24.573
from the old
world trade center here

52:24.575 --> 52:27.343
and I think all of us
never want to see

52:27.345 --> 52:29.678
anything like that happen
again, and it would have
been a lot harder

52:29.680 --> 52:31.413
for 9/11 to ever have occurred

52:31.415 --> 52:32.681
had we had
the protections in place

52:32.683 --> 52:34.483
that would prevent the movement

52:34.485 --> 52:36.886
of massive amounts of money
around the globe

52:36.888 --> 52:41.257
by people who would
want to kill everybody
in this room,

52:41.259 --> 52:44.260
so I think the key is

52:44.262 --> 52:46.662
to not create useless regulation

52:46.664 --> 52:50.266
but I think the motives
behind a lot of those rules

52:50.268 --> 52:54.170
are to ensure we don't
miss something again.

52:55.405 --> 52:56.839
Since 2001,

52:56.841 --> 53:00.342
there's this absurd
obsession with terrorism.

53:00.344 --> 53:02.578
So any time a regulary
gets up and says,

53:02.580 --> 53:04.446
"well, bitcoin can be used
for terrorism."

53:04.448 --> 53:06.415
Well, of course it can.
So can anything.

53:06.417 --> 53:08.851
So can cell phones
and so can the Internet
and so can the car.

53:08.853 --> 53:12.521
It doesn't mean that
we should stifle the growth
of those industries

53:12.523 --> 53:14.356
just because bad people
can use it.

53:29.906 --> 53:31.941
This has arguably been
the worst week

53:31.943 --> 53:33.809
in the cryptocurrency's
short life,

53:33.811 --> 53:38.247
stunned by the collapse
of once-dominant exchange
mt. Gox.

53:38.249 --> 53:42.351
Now that failed firm's ceo
mark karpeles is in hiding.

53:42.353 --> 53:46.789
Some 750,000 bitcoins
allegedly stolen or lost

53:46.791 --> 53:50.626
which accounts for about 6%
of the total circulation.

53:52.429 --> 53:53.963
By the time
mt. Gox went down,

53:53.965 --> 53:56.999
it was holding what
its customers believed

53:57.001 --> 53:59.468
were about
a half a billion dollars

53:59.470 --> 54:02.271
worth of their bitcoins
and the company's bitcoins.

54:02.273 --> 54:05.674
It was no longer the largest
exchange in the world.

54:05.676 --> 54:07.710
But part of what's so amazing is

54:07.712 --> 54:10.446
that people kept using it

54:10.448 --> 54:13.515
even after there had been
numerous incidents

54:13.517 --> 54:15.351
in which it was clear
that the company

54:15.353 --> 54:17.953
was not up to the task
of safeguarding the money.

54:24.861 --> 54:27.463
And the only reason he survived
as long as he did

54:27.465 --> 54:29.865
was because in 2013,
the price started going up.

54:29.867 --> 54:31.667
People kept
putting money into it.

54:31.669 --> 54:33.902
He had more and more money
'cause the price was going up,

54:33.904 --> 54:35.804
but as soon as
the price started going down,

54:35.806 --> 54:36.805
this is what happened, right?

54:36.807 --> 54:39.375
It peaks in late 2013.

54:39.377 --> 54:40.876
It starts coming down in 2014.

54:40.878 --> 54:43.012
Soon as that price
started coming down,

54:43.014 --> 54:45.347
it all just tumbled for him.

54:45.349 --> 54:47.449
Gox was going to collapse.

54:47.451 --> 54:48.917
That it lasted as long as it did

54:48.919 --> 54:51.954
was actually
kind of a stroke of fate.

54:51.956 --> 54:53.522
But its failure was

54:53.524 --> 54:55.524
it didn't have
the kind of more boring

54:55.526 --> 54:57.059
mainstream
institutional controls

54:57.061 --> 54:59.828
that we require to bring it
to the next level.

54:59.830 --> 55:02.798
And there's a whole bunch
of money missing,

55:02.800 --> 55:04.833
and no one knows
if they just lost it,

55:04.835 --> 55:05.934
it if was stolen from them,

55:05.936 --> 55:08.370
if they embezzled it or what,

55:08.372 --> 55:10.973
but the important
lesson from gox

55:10.975 --> 55:13.342
isn't that bitcoin doesn't work.

55:13.344 --> 55:15.377
The important lesson from gox

55:15.379 --> 55:17.579
is that you don't
leave your money with
a trusted third party

55:17.581 --> 55:19.515
because you can't
always trust them.

55:19.517 --> 55:20.949
You can only trust them
until you can't.

55:20.951 --> 55:22.751
This was also a lesson
that people were

55:22.753 --> 55:24.086
supposed to learn
during the financial crisis

55:24.088 --> 55:26.588
but they don't seem
to have learned it yet.

55:29.059 --> 55:30.693
Mark karpeles

55:30.695 --> 55:32.761
was a gamer.

55:32.763 --> 55:35.030
He was not a finance pro.

55:35.032 --> 55:37.700
He really didn't know
what he was doing,

55:37.702 --> 55:40.769
and he didn't build it.
Jed mccaleb built it.

55:40.771 --> 55:42.371
He didn't improve upon it.

55:42.373 --> 55:44.573
I mean, it lurched
from crisis to crisis

55:44.575 --> 55:46.809
throughout the entire history.

55:46.811 --> 55:50.679
Last year was
a terrible year for bitcoin,

55:50.681 --> 55:52.648
and an especially
terrible year for
the foundation,

55:52.650 --> 55:55.851
because we had
two of the people
on our board of directors

55:55.853 --> 55:59.621
who had to resign
in disgrace, basically.

55:59.623 --> 56:02.491
You know, my expertise
is technology.

56:02.493 --> 56:05.361
My expertise is not
figuring out, like,

56:05.363 --> 56:06.995
who's trustworthy, who's not,

56:06.997 --> 56:08.831
which businesses
are gonna succeed,

56:08.833 --> 56:10.899
which businesses are gonna fail.

56:10.901 --> 56:12.868
After we had held our hearings,

56:12.870 --> 56:17.806
we thought we would take
six months to nine months,
even a year,

56:17.808 --> 56:19.742
to draft
our initial regulations.

56:19.744 --> 56:21.410
This was so complicated
that we wanted

56:21.412 --> 56:23.846
to really take our time
and get it right.

56:23.848 --> 56:26.782
What happened was, though,
mt. Gox collapsed.

56:26.784 --> 56:28.050
And I think that gave us

56:28.052 --> 56:30.419
a real renewed sense of urgency,

56:30.421 --> 56:33.122
and we realized that
if we got regulation right,

56:33.124 --> 56:36.492
we could create more confidence
in bitcoin, frankly,

56:36.494 --> 56:38.927
as opposed to the sort of
loss of confidence you saw

56:38.929 --> 56:41.530
not only from the silk road case

56:41.532 --> 56:43.399
but also from the collapse
of mt. Gox.

56:43.401 --> 56:44.967
So your sense, though,

56:44.969 --> 56:46.735
of the regulators, right now.

56:46.737 --> 56:47.903
I assume you've
had conversations.

56:47.905 --> 56:49.505
The discussions that we've had,

56:49.507 --> 56:51.473
I think everybody
recognizes the innovation

56:51.475 --> 56:53.075
and doesn't want to stifle it.

56:53.077 --> 56:55.444
They just want to make sure
that there's healthy regulation

56:55.446 --> 56:58.514
so it's used in a safe
and productive manner.

57:00.784 --> 57:03.118
I'm not giving up on New York.
New York's giving up on me.

57:03.120 --> 57:05.654
I can't even turn on
the bitcoin machine.

57:05.656 --> 57:07.823
An atm, i can't turn it on.

57:07.825 --> 57:10.426
I can't make trades.
I can't do anything.

57:10.428 --> 57:14.196
There's no cash flow at all.

57:14.198 --> 57:16.165
And it's potential regulation.

57:16.167 --> 57:19.568
It's regulations
i should believe

57:19.570 --> 57:21.603
is coming down the pipe.

57:21.605 --> 57:24.840
Like, I don't want to do
anything that someone's
frowning upon

57:24.842 --> 57:27.776
right next door
to the stock market.

57:27.778 --> 57:29.077
They're gonna lock me up.

57:29.079 --> 57:30.846
You know, you can't
have an exchange.

57:30.848 --> 57:32.648
Well, we don't.
People meet there

57:32.650 --> 57:33.949
and exchange with each other.

57:33.951 --> 57:36.185
New York's sitting there
on the high horse,

57:36.187 --> 57:38.220
and the whole world's waiting

57:38.222 --> 57:41.757
on New York to create
some fuckin' license.

57:50.133 --> 57:52.734
Ultimately lawsky's office
brought out

57:52.736 --> 57:54.636
the final rules
for the bitlicense

57:54.638 --> 57:56.538
in the spring of 2015.

57:56.540 --> 58:00.909
A lot of companies complained
that the regulations

58:00.911 --> 58:04.146
were too burdensome for them
to operate in New York

58:04.148 --> 58:05.647
and still make money.

58:05.649 --> 58:07.249
I saw just overnight

58:07.251 --> 58:09.852
dozens of companies that were
on the verge of launching.

58:09.854 --> 58:12.621
They just threw in the towel
and said, "we can't
afford this."

58:12.623 --> 58:14.823
Erik voorhees' new company
shapeshift

58:14.825 --> 58:16.959
would have had to apply
for the bitlicense

58:16.961 --> 58:19.528
if it wanted to keep
customers in New York.

58:21.064 --> 58:23.665
So, in my lap here
i have the...

58:23.667 --> 58:25.934
The application forms
for license to engage

58:25.936 --> 58:28.170
in virtual currency
business activity,

58:28.172 --> 58:31.940
which is a very statist way
of saying the bitlicense.

58:31.942 --> 58:35.244
The is the application
to be approved

58:35.246 --> 58:39.848
to do basically what we've
all been doing for years now,

58:39.850 --> 58:41.884
which is building bitcoin
companies in New York.

58:41.886 --> 58:45.821
And a lot of
stuff in here I personally
feel is unethical,

58:45.823 --> 58:47.523
so we're not gonna
comply with it,

58:47.525 --> 58:49.091
which means we have to block
new yorkers entirely.

58:49.093 --> 58:50.559
And when an entire new industry

58:50.561 --> 58:52.094
starts blocking
a place like New York

58:52.096 --> 58:54.663
that used to be the financial
center of the world,

58:54.665 --> 58:58.667
hopefully some of those
politicians will take notice.

58:58.669 --> 59:00.135
The point of it is to, one,

59:00.137 --> 59:01.870
make sure there are enough
consumer protections;

59:01.872 --> 59:04.573
two, make sure we have
adequate cybersecurity;

59:04.575 --> 59:09.077
three, make sure that
the companies are adequately
capitalized

59:09.079 --> 59:11.213
so they don't collapse
upon themselves.

59:11.215 --> 59:14.182
You know, you've seen
a tug of war

59:14.184 --> 59:17.319
between the hard liners
and those who are saying,

59:17.321 --> 59:18.887
"you know, you've got to have

59:18.889 --> 59:21.690
enough space
for innovation in here,"

59:21.692 --> 59:24.026
and the system has come out,
i think,

59:24.028 --> 59:26.828
probably stronger
as a result of that

59:26.830 --> 59:28.664
and there's a widespread view

59:28.666 --> 59:30.866
amongst certainly
the business bitcoin community

59:30.868 --> 59:33.268
that some level of regulation

59:33.270 --> 59:35.003
gives legitimacy
to what they're doing.

59:35.005 --> 59:36.705
It gives people
confidence in what
they're doing.

59:36.707 --> 59:39.074
This is an important part
of growing up.

59:39.076 --> 59:41.143
Ultimately, they're not
going to get it right,

59:41.145 --> 59:44.079
because no regulation
is ever right.

59:44.081 --> 59:46.248
But I'm highly confident

59:46.250 --> 59:49.785
that whatever happens
going forward,

59:49.787 --> 59:51.620
the bitlicense will be looked at

59:51.622 --> 59:53.088
as a positive development

59:53.090 --> 59:55.324
in the evolution of bitcoin

59:55.326 --> 59:58.160
because it just removed
one of the biggest pieces
of uncertainty,

59:58.162 --> 01:00:01.263
which is how is this industry
going to be regulated.

01:00:01.265 --> 01:00:05.267
I think most of us...
At least a lot of us...

01:00:05.269 --> 01:00:07.269
Think that sensible regulation

01:00:07.271 --> 01:00:08.670
that sets guidelines

01:00:08.672 --> 01:00:10.739
that makes sure people's money

01:00:10.741 --> 01:00:12.908
doesn't just go into
a black hole

01:00:12.910 --> 01:00:15.677
that that's
a really important thing,

01:00:15.679 --> 01:00:17.179
that regulation.

01:00:17.181 --> 01:00:19.281
I'm sure satoshi
wouldn't be happy

01:00:19.283 --> 01:00:20.782
to see this kind of thing,

01:00:20.784 --> 01:00:22.718
which is not based
on the logic and reason

01:00:22.720 --> 01:00:24.186
that a programmer is used to.

01:00:24.188 --> 01:00:26.989
I think a lot of developers,
understandably so,

01:00:26.991 --> 01:00:31.393
try to stay out of
the political nonsense.

01:00:31.395 --> 01:00:33.662
It has been one of
the biggest mysteries

01:00:33.664 --> 01:00:34.863
raging across the Internet:

01:00:34.865 --> 01:00:36.898
Who is satoshi nakamoto?

01:00:36.900 --> 01:00:38.734
Newsweek published an article

01:00:38.736 --> 01:00:41.336
claiming the man
in these images is
the bitcoin founder.

01:00:41.338 --> 01:00:43.405
The man who created bitcoin,

01:00:43.407 --> 01:00:45.140
is known as
the father of bitcoin,

01:00:45.142 --> 01:00:49.011
the online currency
now worth billions.

01:00:49.013 --> 01:00:50.712
When you asked him
about bitcoin,

01:00:50.714 --> 01:00:52.948
and he says, "i can't talk
about this anymore,"

01:00:52.950 --> 01:00:54.883
he was not referring to bitcoin.

01:00:54.885 --> 01:00:57.252
But with me, he definitely
acknowledged bitcoin.

01:00:57.254 --> 01:00:58.720
I think at this point now
he's saying

01:00:58.722 --> 01:01:00.656
he was confused
by the conversation.

01:01:01.724 --> 01:01:02.891
Clearly somebody thought

01:01:02.893 --> 01:01:05.093
that we did this
as an act of war

01:01:05.095 --> 01:01:06.995
against satoshi nakamoto
or bitcoin,

01:01:06.997 --> 01:01:08.330
and I want to be very clear

01:01:08.332 --> 01:01:12.067
that I certainly never
meant it that way.

01:01:12.069 --> 01:01:14.870
I have nothing to do
with bitcoin.

01:01:14.872 --> 01:01:17.673
It was a monster story.

01:01:17.675 --> 01:01:19.107
How did they figure it out?

01:01:19.109 --> 01:01:20.809
Oh, my god, look at
this guy that they named.

01:01:20.811 --> 01:01:23.111
His name is
Dorian satoshi nakamoto,

01:01:23.113 --> 01:01:24.913
living in California,

01:01:24.915 --> 01:01:26.682
basically hiding in plain sight.

01:01:26.684 --> 01:01:29.785
It becomes a gigantic
media scramble,

01:01:29.787 --> 01:01:31.920
and then Dorian emerges
from his house

01:01:31.922 --> 01:01:34.389
looking kind of disheveled,
looking kind of confused,

01:01:34.391 --> 01:01:37.325
and says
he's not satoshi nakamoto,

01:01:37.327 --> 01:01:39.194
says he's never heard
of bitcoin.

01:01:39.196 --> 01:01:41.029
He doesn't understand.
He had one conversation
with Leah.

01:01:41.031 --> 01:01:42.230
She misunderstood what he said,

01:01:42.232 --> 01:01:45.033
she took it the wrong way.

01:01:45.035 --> 01:01:48.036
And you probably would have
had to have been
a cypherpunk

01:01:48.038 --> 01:01:49.805
to understand all
the elements of it

01:01:49.807 --> 01:01:51.339
that had already been
put together.

01:01:51.341 --> 01:01:53.241
The odds of it seemed
very low to me

01:01:53.243 --> 01:01:55.811
that it was somebody
from completely outside
that community

01:01:55.813 --> 01:01:58.080
who happened to know
all these different things

01:01:58.082 --> 01:02:00.382
and put this together
and appear out of nowhere.

01:02:03.152 --> 01:02:05.387
The day that "newsweek's"
story came out

01:02:05.389 --> 01:02:07.956
naming Dorian nakamoto
as the creator of bitcoin,

01:02:07.958 --> 01:02:10.258
I got this email
from an old acquaintance

01:02:10.260 --> 01:02:12.794
that was titled
"what are the odds?"

01:02:12.796 --> 01:02:17.232
And it laid out the fact
that hal Finney

01:02:17.234 --> 01:02:20.102
lives less than
two miles away from

01:02:20.104 --> 01:02:22.137
the known address
of Dorian nakamoto

01:02:22.139 --> 01:02:23.972
where "newsweek" had found him.

01:02:23.974 --> 01:02:27.209
And hal Finney is the number two
ever user of bitcoin,

01:02:27.211 --> 01:02:30.011
who received the first
bitcoin transaction.

01:02:30.013 --> 01:02:32.447
He worked on an early prototype

01:02:32.449 --> 01:02:34.349
of an anonymous currency system.

01:02:34.351 --> 01:02:36.151
He was a cypherpunk.

01:02:38.287 --> 01:02:41.289
So how could it be
that the purported creator
of bitcoin

01:02:41.291 --> 01:02:44.893
and this known, confirmed,
second-ever user of bitcoin,

01:02:44.895 --> 01:02:46.394
hadn't ever collaborated?

01:02:46.396 --> 01:02:48.864
That hal Finney, who was less
than two miles away

01:02:48.866 --> 01:02:51.366
from Dorian nakamoto
hadn't helped to create bitcoin?

01:02:51.368 --> 01:02:54.002
Or maybe he really was
the creator of bitcoin.

01:02:54.004 --> 01:02:56.538
Maybe hal Finney
was satoshi nakamoto.

01:02:58.441 --> 01:03:00.909
When you look at
the bitcoin white paper,

01:03:00.911 --> 01:03:05.147
it made reference to
a lot of the earlier projects

01:03:05.149 --> 01:03:07.182
that fed into bitcoin.

01:03:07.184 --> 01:03:11.553
But it's very notable
that the one project
it doesn't refer to

01:03:11.555 --> 01:03:13.255
is Nick szabo's bit gold,

01:03:13.257 --> 01:03:15.257
which is perhaps
the closest precedent

01:03:15.259 --> 01:03:18.527
and the closest parallel
to bitcoin.

01:03:18.529 --> 01:03:20.362
I mean, bit gold
is so close to bitcoin,

01:03:20.364 --> 01:03:21.830
it's hard not to think

01:03:21.832 --> 01:03:25.901
that, you know,
maybe Nick is satoshi.

01:03:28.070 --> 01:03:31.106
A lot of people will say
"nakamoto must be szabo."

01:03:31.108 --> 01:03:32.440
"Nakamoto
must have been Finney."

01:03:32.442 --> 01:03:34.543
But I don't think
he was trying to leave

01:03:34.545 --> 01:03:37.279
any breadcrumbs out there
for anybody to follow.

01:03:39.549 --> 01:03:41.149
I told my editor about it.

01:03:41.151 --> 01:03:43.852
He agreed that
"you found satoshi nakamoto."

01:03:43.854 --> 01:03:46.021
So I got on a plane
to Santa Barbara

01:03:46.023 --> 01:03:48.590
and I drove out
to hal Finney's house.

01:03:48.592 --> 01:03:51.393
But at this stage,
he was already

01:03:51.395 --> 01:03:53.862
completely paralyzed by als,

01:03:53.864 --> 01:03:57.933
this really awful,
debilitating terminal illness

01:03:57.935 --> 01:04:00.502
that slowly shuts down your body

01:04:00.504 --> 01:04:03.505
while leaving your mind
completely intact.

01:04:03.507 --> 01:04:07.442
And the time when
he started to fade in
his physical abilities

01:04:07.444 --> 01:04:09.177
did roughly coincide
with the time

01:04:09.179 --> 01:04:11.446
that satoshi nakamoto
started to disappear.

01:04:11.448 --> 01:04:13.348
Now maybe the reason
that satoshi nakamoto

01:04:13.350 --> 01:04:15.517
had chosen to fade away

01:04:15.519 --> 01:04:18.553
was because hal Finney
was physically fading.

01:04:21.457 --> 01:04:25.126
There have been a number
of stylometric studies

01:04:25.128 --> 01:04:28.096
and you see so many
of these similarities

01:04:28.098 --> 01:04:30.866
between satoshi's writings
and those of Nick's,

01:04:30.868 --> 01:04:33.535
including these little things
like having two spaces

01:04:33.537 --> 01:04:35.203
at the beginning of a sentence,

01:04:35.205 --> 01:04:38.073
and phrases and spellings
that nobody else uses.

01:04:39.642 --> 01:04:43.245
So I talked to hal as much as i
could, mostly in a kind of

01:04:43.247 --> 01:04:49.417
one-way interview because he
could really only respond
with yes and no answers,

01:04:49.419 --> 01:04:52.053
and he denied being
satoshi nakamoto.

01:04:52.055 --> 01:04:54.122
You could tell
that he was amused
by the whole idea

01:04:54.124 --> 01:04:55.590
that I thought
he was satoshi nakamoto.

01:04:55.592 --> 01:04:58.960
One of the really
remarkable things

01:04:58.962 --> 01:05:00.228
from Nick szabo's writing

01:05:00.230 --> 01:05:02.564
in those months before bitcoin

01:05:02.566 --> 01:05:06.334
was publically launched
is that Nick,

01:05:06.336 --> 01:05:08.403
in responding to some comments

01:05:08.405 --> 01:05:11.072
about a post he had made
about bit gold,

01:05:11.074 --> 01:05:14.242
actually asked the other people
who were reading him

01:05:14.244 --> 01:05:18.313
if anybody wanted to help him
code this idea up

01:05:18.315 --> 01:05:20.982
into real software
that could work.

01:05:20.984 --> 01:05:22.484
It was never turned
into a reality,

01:05:22.486 --> 01:05:24.486
but when you look at bit gold,

01:05:24.488 --> 01:05:29.257
it's hard not to be struck
by the similarities

01:05:29.259 --> 01:05:32.360
between it and bitcoin.

01:05:38.167 --> 01:05:40.101
It's possible.

01:05:40.103 --> 01:05:42.203
Hal could've been the coder.

01:05:44.206 --> 01:05:46.007
I don't know.

01:05:46.009 --> 01:05:47.575
You know, this idea that...
That hal Finney could've been

01:05:47.577 --> 01:05:51.947
the kind of ghost coder
for bitcoin...

01:05:51.949 --> 01:05:54.649
I guess it's possible.

01:05:54.651 --> 01:05:57.052
Other people kind of
speculating on reddit

01:05:57.054 --> 01:05:59.120
or other parts of the Internet

01:05:59.122 --> 01:06:01.289
thought that maybe hal Finney

01:06:01.291 --> 01:06:04.225
had used Dorian nakamoto
as a patsy.

01:06:04.227 --> 01:06:07.228
If he were ever traced
back to Dorian nakamoto,

01:06:07.230 --> 01:06:10.231
it seemed like this guy
was the creator,

01:06:10.233 --> 01:06:13.268
and hal Finney would be
sort of immunized from it.

01:06:13.270 --> 01:06:17.205
Everyone else who was
involved in the projects

01:06:17.207 --> 01:06:19.641
leading up to bitcoin
has released

01:06:19.643 --> 01:06:23.645
their communications
with satoshi from this period.

01:06:23.647 --> 01:06:25.647
Nick has avoided doing that,

01:06:25.649 --> 01:06:28.516
and essentially went silent
in those critical months

01:06:28.518 --> 01:06:30.585
after bitcoin was released.

01:06:30.587 --> 01:06:33.355
You know, when you talk
to people face to face,

01:06:33.357 --> 01:06:35.423
and they tell you these things,

01:06:35.425 --> 01:06:39.427
you can get a sense
if they're being honest.

01:06:39.429 --> 01:06:42.030
If hal Finney actually
had a secret

01:06:42.032 --> 01:06:44.132
billion-dollar cache
of bitcoins,

01:06:44.134 --> 01:06:47.068
he wouldn't have been able
to lie to me so effectively
about it.

01:06:47.070 --> 01:06:50.739
In the end, the reasons
to believe that this was
all just a coincidence

01:06:50.741 --> 01:06:54.442
began to outweigh
the coincidence itself.

01:06:54.444 --> 01:06:55.710
It's almost like an eel.

01:06:55.712 --> 01:06:58.046
There's something there,
you can see it,

01:06:58.048 --> 01:07:00.315
but as soon as you touch it
it just slides right out
of your hands

01:07:00.317 --> 01:07:01.716
and you're left with nothing.

01:07:02.785 --> 01:07:04.719
Anybody who is of any note

01:07:04.721 --> 01:07:06.121
in the cypherpunk movement,

01:07:06.123 --> 01:07:07.155
and even outside of it too,

01:07:07.157 --> 01:07:09.057
has at one time or another

01:07:09.059 --> 01:07:10.458
been called satoshi.

01:07:10.460 --> 01:07:12.527
Hal Finney denied it.
Nick szabo denied it.

01:07:12.529 --> 01:07:13.795
They've all denied it.

01:07:13.797 --> 01:07:15.797
Maybe one of them is satoshi.

01:07:15.799 --> 01:07:17.599
Maybe all of them are satoshi.

01:07:17.601 --> 01:07:19.667
It really is a mystery.

01:07:55.304 --> 01:07:57.705
That's the original ticker

01:07:57.707 --> 01:08:00.375
from next door.

01:08:00.377 --> 01:08:02.510
All right, so we're over here.

01:08:02.512 --> 01:08:06.281
Bitcoin center, 100 feet from
the stock exchange, over here.

01:08:06.283 --> 01:08:09.117
And, uh...

01:08:09.119 --> 01:08:11.152
You know, some of you guys
took a hit last week,

01:08:11.154 --> 01:08:14.622
last couple of weeks.

01:08:14.624 --> 01:08:16.191
Lot of the big guys,

01:08:16.193 --> 01:08:20.528
they got their foothold
in the business

01:08:20.529 --> 01:08:24.131
that they weren't a part of
in the beginning.

01:08:26.569 --> 01:08:28.269
I don't know what's going on.

01:08:28.270 --> 01:08:30.337
But, uh, I don't know.

01:08:30.340 --> 01:08:32.140
I wouldn't write off
bitcoin that easy.

01:08:32.142 --> 01:08:34.509
I know that bitcoin
is gonna change the world.

01:08:34.511 --> 01:08:36.411
It's changing the world already.

01:08:36.412 --> 01:08:39.613
And we have to stand tall

01:08:39.616 --> 01:08:42.884
and proud

01:08:42.886 --> 01:08:45.752
as bitcoiners
and early adopters.

01:08:45.755 --> 01:08:48.189
They don't know anything
about new technology,

01:08:48.191 --> 01:08:52.359
but once it starts making sense,

01:08:52.362 --> 01:08:53.795
they throw their dollars
behind it.

01:09:00.870 --> 01:09:03.238
You know, unfortunately,

01:09:06.274 --> 01:09:09.644
early adopters

01:09:09.645 --> 01:09:13.648
make the roads
that we all travel down,

01:09:13.649 --> 01:09:17.252
and they are usually paved over
in the process.

01:09:17.254 --> 01:09:20.220
The first guy
through the door gets shot.

01:09:20.223 --> 01:09:22.256
You know, but somebody's
gotta go through the door,

01:09:22.259 --> 01:09:24.559
but they're gonna get shot.

01:09:24.560 --> 01:09:26.794
Charlie shrem, Ross albricht,

01:09:26.796 --> 01:09:28.496
Julian Assange,

01:09:28.497 --> 01:09:31.432
they got shot
coming through the door.

01:09:31.434 --> 01:09:35.870
But we're all utilizing
the freedoms

01:09:35.872 --> 01:09:38.372
and technologies afforded to us

01:09:38.375 --> 01:09:39.841
because they knocked
the door down.

01:09:41.844 --> 01:09:43.511
Hey, Michael.

01:09:43.513 --> 01:09:45.680
Can I put you
on speakerphone
for a minute?

01:09:45.682 --> 01:09:48.316
If I know how.

01:09:48.318 --> 01:09:51.752
Hey, Michael, can I ask you,
where did you buy bitcoins?

01:09:53.455 --> 01:09:54.656
Yeah.

01:09:58.227 --> 01:10:00.495
Did you lose... how much...
Do you still have them?

01:10:05.334 --> 01:10:06.401
You put into it.

01:10:06.403 --> 01:10:08.269
Can you use it?

01:10:08.271 --> 01:10:11.472
Do I want to buy it?
No, not today.

01:10:11.474 --> 01:10:13.675
Though it is going to be around.

01:10:16.579 --> 01:10:19.547
Did you ever use it
to buy anything?

01:10:22.585 --> 01:10:25.220
- Michael.

01:10:27.756 --> 01:10:28.923
No, okay.

01:10:28.925 --> 01:10:31.793
They should go back to,
you know,

01:10:31.795 --> 01:10:33.928
day one and just start all over.

01:10:33.930 --> 01:10:36.698
Forget about bitcoin,
call it something else.

01:10:36.700 --> 01:10:39.400
I think it's been
so tarnished now

01:10:39.402 --> 01:10:42.437
with this...
With the silk road...

01:10:44.740 --> 01:10:47.442
You know, I just think,
you know,

01:10:47.444 --> 01:10:51.012
that all that stuff about
$400 million disappearing

01:10:51.014 --> 01:10:55.250
and... you're just not
gonna get off the ground.

01:10:55.252 --> 01:10:56.718
Nobody's gonna...

01:10:56.720 --> 01:10:57.852
You know,
like Warren buffet said,

01:10:57.854 --> 01:10:59.387
"stay the hell away from it."

01:11:03.359 --> 01:11:05.260
To put all the cards
on the table,

01:11:05.262 --> 01:11:07.662
I'm gonna be
leaving the department
in the coming weeks.

01:11:07.664 --> 01:11:12.300
And if you asked me
back when I took this job
in 2011

01:11:12.302 --> 01:11:16.571
what I thought
we'd be working on
during my tenure,

01:11:16.573 --> 01:11:19.841
digital currencies
would not have been
at the top of the list.

01:11:26.715 --> 01:11:28.716
So Ben lawsky created
this thing call the bitlicense

01:11:28.718 --> 01:11:32.620
which is New York's
attempt to regulate

01:11:32.622 --> 01:11:35.556
this scary new technology.
It's now law.

01:11:35.558 --> 01:11:39.060
And he has announced
that he is leaving government

01:11:39.062 --> 01:11:42.664
in order to set up his own
private consulting firm

01:11:42.666 --> 01:11:46.601
to help companies navigate
financial regulations

01:11:46.603 --> 01:11:48.903
such as the bitlicense
that he created.

01:11:48.905 --> 01:11:52.607
So we essentially had this
beautiful new ecosystem
being built,

01:11:52.609 --> 01:11:55.310
and Ben lawsky comes by,

01:11:55.312 --> 01:11:56.611
says, "I'm here
to protect consumers."

01:11:56.613 --> 01:11:57.979
He builds a huge
wall around the thing,

01:11:57.981 --> 01:11:59.080
and then he sits
outside the gate

01:11:59.082 --> 01:12:01.082
charging people to get in.

01:12:01.084 --> 01:12:03.718
This is the very definition
of crony capitalism,

01:12:03.720 --> 01:12:06.321
and, for some reason,

01:12:06.323 --> 01:12:08.403
Ben lawsky doesn't even see
anything wrong with that.

01:12:09.958 --> 01:12:11.726
I think history
will not judge him

01:12:11.728 --> 01:12:13.861
as favorably as he thinks.

01:12:16.098 --> 01:12:17.632
So, um, yeah.

01:12:17.634 --> 01:12:21.002
I've started up
my own consulting business.

01:12:21.004 --> 01:12:22.570
It's been quite interesting.

01:12:22.572 --> 01:12:24.505
Doing a lot of work
in the fintech space,

01:12:24.507 --> 01:12:27.775
but also doing work
with a lot of traditional
companies

01:12:27.777 --> 01:12:29.977
in the financial services
world as well.

01:12:29.979 --> 01:12:34.048
Ben lawsky's team at the dfs

01:12:34.050 --> 01:12:37.352
that was working on
this bitlicense

01:12:37.354 --> 01:12:38.653
and the bitcoin initiative

01:12:38.655 --> 01:12:40.988
have all ended up
leaving the agency

01:12:40.990 --> 01:12:42.757
and going to consulting firms

01:12:42.759 --> 01:12:45.860
that are now working
on these issues.

01:12:45.862 --> 01:12:50.665
Danny alter is going
to work for itbit

01:12:50.667 --> 01:12:52.834
and Dana Syracuse
is going to work for

01:12:52.836 --> 01:12:54.602
the consulting firm k2.

01:12:54.604 --> 01:12:56.604
Itbit is particularly notable

01:12:56.606 --> 01:12:59.907
because they were
the first to find a way

01:12:59.909 --> 01:13:03.077
to partner with the dfs
to get licensed

01:13:03.079 --> 01:13:05.680
to open their own
bitcoin exchange.

01:13:10.152 --> 01:13:11.786
When this is over,

01:13:11.788 --> 01:13:14.455
definitely going to leave
New York when I can.

01:13:14.457 --> 01:13:16.057
Where I'm gonna go,
i don't know.

01:13:16.059 --> 01:13:18.526
I think the bitcoin community
in New York is done with.

01:13:18.528 --> 01:13:20.094
No, it doesn't foster
innovation here.

