01:14:57.594 --> 01:15:01.729
in any meaningful sense
until 2014,

01:15:01.731 --> 01:15:04.131
late in the year,
and at the time,

01:15:04.133 --> 01:15:08.636
my perspective was one
of skepticism, I would say.

01:15:08.638 --> 01:15:12.206
Specifically because
the storyline that I heard

01:15:12.208 --> 01:15:15.543
related very much
to cryptocurrency

01:15:15.545 --> 01:15:18.646
as a potential medium
of exchange and store of value,

01:15:18.648 --> 01:15:22.016
which is a valid debate
and application,

01:15:22.018 --> 01:15:26.220
but it doesn't have
full extent of the power

01:15:26.222 --> 01:15:29.991
that the underlying technology
has to achieve.

01:15:31.159 --> 01:15:34.262
Blythe masters
is not just any banker.

01:15:34.264 --> 01:15:38.699
She is this person
who I think is really seen

01:15:38.701 --> 01:15:42.270
as being behind
some of the most
problematic innovations

01:15:42.272 --> 01:15:45.873
in the financial industry
over the last three decades.

01:15:45.875 --> 01:15:48.309
Blythe is the one who's
essentially given credit

01:15:48.311 --> 01:15:51.178
for creating
the credit default swap

01:15:51.180 --> 01:15:55.983
which essentially
provides a way to bet
on the default of a bond,

01:15:55.985 --> 01:15:59.887
and the credit default swap
ended up taking this place

01:15:59.889 --> 01:16:02.089
at the center
of the financial crisis

01:16:02.091 --> 01:16:04.559
and these bets
that banks had made

01:16:04.561 --> 01:16:07.028
against sub-prime
mortgages.

01:16:08.297 --> 01:16:11.098
Blockchain technology eradicates

01:16:11.100 --> 01:16:13.834
a significant amount
of inefficiency in the system,

01:16:13.836 --> 01:16:15.770
and reduces costs.

01:16:15.772 --> 01:16:18.272
It doesn't mean
that we are doing away

01:16:18.274 --> 01:16:21.676
with the need for trust
in financial services at all.

01:16:23.045 --> 01:16:25.980
Bitcoin was designed
to find a way

01:16:25.982 --> 01:16:27.715
to circumvent wall street,

01:16:27.717 --> 01:16:30.017
and what blythe masters is doing

01:16:30.019 --> 01:16:32.219
is essentially
trying to find ways

01:16:32.221 --> 01:16:35.590
to bring wall street
into bitcoin

01:16:35.592 --> 01:16:38.893
and make it possible for them
to use this technology
as well.

01:16:38.895 --> 01:16:41.929
What the bankers seem to be
looking to do at this point

01:16:41.931 --> 01:16:45.700
is create their own
private blockchain,

01:16:45.702 --> 01:16:48.069
where their computers
are powering it.

01:16:48.071 --> 01:16:50.738
Rather than
these anonymous miners,

01:16:50.740 --> 01:16:53.307
they want control
over the system.

01:16:53.309 --> 01:16:58.379
The banks are looking
at this incredibly wide array

01:16:58.381 --> 01:17:01.048
of ways that
they might use this,

01:17:01.050 --> 01:17:04.619
which include replacing
stock exchanges,

01:17:04.621 --> 01:17:08.022
finding new ways
to originate loans,

01:17:08.024 --> 01:17:12.393
finding new ways to move money
between countries,

01:17:12.395 --> 01:17:14.028
and, of course,
that's going back

01:17:14.030 --> 01:17:17.064
to the original idea of bitcoin,

01:17:17.066 --> 01:17:20.635
but now it's happening within
these financial institutions

01:17:20.637 --> 01:17:24.038
rather than outside it,
as bitcoin had imagined.

01:17:25.774 --> 01:17:27.975
I have no problem
with the banking system

01:17:27.977 --> 01:17:29.910
and the financial industry
co-opting bitcoin,

01:17:29.912 --> 01:17:33.014
primarily because bitcoin
can't really be co-opted.

01:17:33.016 --> 01:17:34.248
The fact that it's decentralized

01:17:34.250 --> 01:17:35.950
means no one can control it,

01:17:35.952 --> 01:17:39.720
no matter who they are
or how much money they have.

01:17:39.722 --> 01:17:41.188
I think it's
all good for bitcoin.

01:17:41.190 --> 01:17:42.757
I think all of the innovation
that's happening,

01:17:42.759 --> 01:17:45.026
both on wall street
and in silicon valley

01:17:45.028 --> 01:17:47.028
I think competition
will take care of

01:17:47.030 --> 01:17:48.996
people who want to try
to have a monopoly,

01:17:48.998 --> 01:17:53.000
or who want to try to charge
more than they should

01:17:53.002 --> 01:17:54.268
for whatever product or service

01:17:54.270 --> 01:17:56.137
that is happening
on the blockchain.

01:17:56.139 --> 01:17:57.972
It really is as advertised.

01:17:57.974 --> 01:18:00.841
It really is controlled by all
the people who are using it,

01:18:00.843 --> 01:18:04.745
and it really is designed
just to be a more efficient,

01:18:04.747 --> 01:18:08.315
more fair way of sending
value over the Internet.

